[[Renewable energy]] is generally defined as energy that comes from [[Renewable resource|resources]] which are naturally replenished on a human timescale, such as [[sunlight]], [[wind]], [[rain]], [[tidal power|tides]], [[wave power|waves]], and [[geothermal energy|geothermal heat]].<ref>Omar Ellabban, Haitham Abu-Rub, Frede Blaabjerg, ''Renewable energy resources: Current status, future prospects and their enabling technology. [[Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews]] 39, (2014), 748–764, p 749, {{DOI|10.1016/j.rser.2014.07.113}}.</ref> Renewable energy replaces conventional fuels in four distinct areas: [[electricity generation]], air and water heating/cooling, [[motor fuel]]s, and [[Stand-alone power system|rural (off-grid)]] energy services.<ref name=ren15>REN21 (2010). [http://www.harbortaxgroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/REN21_GSR_2010_full_revised-Sept2010.pdf Renewables 2010 Global Status Report] p. 15.</ref> Based on [[REN21]]'s 2014 report, renewables contributed 19 percent to our [[World energy consumption|global energy consumption]] and 22 percent to our electricity generation in 2012 and 2013, respectively.<ref name="ria21-GSR2014">{{cite web |url=http://www.ren21.net/Portals/0/documents/Resources/GSR/2014/GSR2014_full%20report_low%20res.pdf |title=Renewables 2014: Global Status Report |author=[[REN21]] |date=2014 |pages=13, 17, 21, 25 |isbn=978-3-9815934-2-6 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SKF06GAX?url=http://www.ren21.net/Portals/0/documents/Resources/GSR/2014/GSR2014_full%20report_low%20res.pdf |archivedate=4 September 2014 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>
