{{Infobox company | name = Petrolex Oil & Gas Ltd. | logo = [[File:Petrolex-logo.png|250px]] | type = [[Private company]] | predecessor = | founder = [[Segun Adebutu]] | foundation = {{start date and age|2007|2}} | location = [[Ikoyi]], [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]] | key_people = Segun Adebutu <small>(Chairman and CEO)</small>, Olukayode Adelaja <small>(Executive director, engineering)</small>, Lilian Ezeilo <small>(Head, external regulatory affairs)</small>, Adeniyi Olowoniyi ([[Chief information officer]]), Modupe Afolabi <small>( H.R. Director)</small> | industry = [[Petroleum industry|Petroleum]] | services = Refining, storage, distribution and retailing of [[petroleum product]]s | products = Oil and Gas | num_employees = 3000 | homepage = {{url|https://petrolex.com/}} }}
'''Petrolex Oil & Gas Limited''' is a [[Nigeria]]n company and part of Petrolex Group, an African integrated energy [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]]. The company was founded in February 2007 by [[Segun Adebutu]], a Nigerian entrepreneur. It provides services to the [[Petroleum industry|oil and gas industry]]. It is mainly involved in the refining, storage, distribution and retail of [[petroleum product]]s in Nigeria and [[Africa]]. Petrolex is best known for starting in December 2017, the construction of a 3.6 billion dollar high capacity refinery and [[Sub-Saharan Africa]]’s largest tank farm as part of its Mega Oil City project in [[Ogun State]], Nigeria.<ref name="bloomnigeria1"/><ref name="guardian1">{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |title= Petrolex Group to launch sub-Saharan Africa’s largest tank farm |url= https://guardian.ng/energy/petrolex-group-to-launch-sub-saharan-africas-largest-tank-farm/ |date= 7 December 2017}}</ref><ref name="vanguardnigeria2"/>
==Background==
Petrolex CEO, Adebutu started an oil and fuel trading business around 2005 but showed interest in “mid-stream infrastructure” for $330 million.<ref name="punchng1">{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Punch| The Punch (Nigeria)]] |title= Petrolex invests $330m in Ogun oil city |url= http://punchng.com/petrolex-invests-330m-in-ogun-oil-city/ |date= December 7, 2017 }}</ref> His experience in family business, laid the foundation for new ideas in his business career. Over the years, Adebutu was involved in bold projects including oil and gas, solid minerals, construction and maritime. This background inspired Adebutu to replicate similar practices with his new initiative Petrolex Oil & Gas Ltd.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://allafrica.com/stories/201712110038.html |work= |publisher= allAfrica |title= Nigeria: Adebutu - We're Investing in Nigeria and Creating a New World of Possibilities |date= 11 December 2017 |accessdate= }}</ref>
In December 2017, Petrolex announced its plan to build a $3.6 billion refinery plant with an output capacity of 250,000 barrels a day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amosun signs agreement with Petrolex on refinery in Ogun |url=https://www.businessdayonline.com/amosun-signs-agreement-with-petrolex-on-refinery-in-ogun/ |date=29 September 2016 |newspaper=[[Business Day (Nigeria)]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.oilreviewafrica.com/exploration/exploration/petrolex-to-develop-us-3-6bn-oil-refinery-in-nigeria |work= |publisher= Oil Review Africa |title= Petrolex to develop US$3.6bn oil refinery in Nigeria |date= 8 December 2017 |accessdate= }}</ref> The company is currently working on the “front-end engineering design” and will complete construction in 2021. This initiative is part of a larger Government program to end petroleum products imports in two years.<ref name="bloomnigeria1">{{cite news |newspaper= [[Bloomberg News]] |title= Nigeria Refining Push Prompts $3.6 Billion Petrolex Plan |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-06/nigeria-s-refining-push-prompts-3-6-billion-plan-from-petrolex |date= December 6, 2017 }}</ref><ref name="cnbcafric">{{cite news |newspaper= [[CNBC Africa]] |title= Petrolex plans 250,000bpd refinery in Nigeria |url= https://www.cnbcafrica.com/videos/2017/12/13/petrolex-plans-250000bpd-refinery-in-nigeria/ |date= December 13, 2017 }}</ref>
With support from partners, Petrolex Group has invested over $330 million in the Ibefun tank farm with a 600,000 million litres monthly capacity.<ref name="vanguardnigeria1">{{cite news |newspaper= [[Vanguard (Nigeria)]] |title= Obasanjo begs FG to support private sector as Osibanjo inaugurates Petrolex tank farm |url= https://www.vanguardngr.com/2017/12/obasanjo-begs-fg-support-private-sector-osibanjo-inaugurates-petrolex-tank-farm/ |date= 12 December 2017 }}</ref> The farm was commissioned by the Vice President of Nigeria [[Yemi Osinbajo]], as part of phase one of a 10-year expansion program.<ref name="newtelegranigeria1">{{cite news |newspaper= [[New Telegraph]] |title= Wema Bank partners Petrolex on $300m tank farm |url= https://newtelegraphonline.com/2017/12/wema-bank-partners-petrolex-300m-tank-farm/ |date= December 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref name="guardian2">{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Guardian (Nigeria)]] |title= Wema Bank seals deal with Petrolex on $300m Ibefun tank farm |url= https://guardian.ng/business-services/wema-bank-seals-deal-with-petrolex-on-300m-ibefun-tank-farm/ |date= 14 December 2017}}</ref> This phase would ease the [[Apapa]] and Ibafon tanker traffic gridlock, a source of anxiety for stakeholders.<ref name="sunnigeria1">{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Sun (Nigeria)]] |title= Petrolex 300m litres tank farm to decongest Apapa by 60% |url= http://sunnewsonline.com/petrolex-300m-litres-tank-farm-to-decongest-apapa-by-60/ |date= 11 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name="independngr">{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Daily Independent (Lagos newspaper)]] |title= Petrolex Mega Oil City Will Ease Apapa Gridlock |url= https://independent.ng/petrolex-mega-oil-city-will-ease-apapa-gridlock/ |date= December 12, 2017}}</ref>
== Petrolex Mega Oil City project==
Petrolex provides services in refining, storage, distribution and retailing of petroleum products. The company intends to be listed on the [[Nigerian Stock Exchange]] in the coming decade. The company launched the planning, design and development of the Petrolex Mega Oil City in Ibefun, Ogun State in 2012. The complex spreads over 101 square kilometres, about 10 percent the size of [[Lagos State]]. It houses a residential estate for staff, an army barracks, 30 loading gantries for product disbursement, and a 4,000 truck capacity trailer park with accommodation for drivers.<ref name="punchng2">{{cite news |newspaper= [[The Punch| The Punch (Nigeria)]] |title= Petrolex to invest $6bn in Nigeria’s oil, gas sector |url= http://punchng.com/petrolex-to-invest-6bn-in-nigerias-oil-gas-sector/ |date= 6 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name="guardian2"/> The Oil City project is the original idea of Segun Adebutu, CEO of Petrolex and son of the Nigerian entrepreneur Sir Kesington Adebutu. Its goal is to create the largest [[Petrochemical industry|petrochemical industrial]] estate in [[Sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.petroleumafrica.com/petrolex-has-funds-for-mega-oil-city/ |work= |publisher= Petroleum Africa |title= Petrolex Has Funds for Mega Oil City |date=December 7, 2017 |accessdate= }}</ref> Upon completion, this estate will include a large capacity refinery,<ref name="cnbcafric"/> a [[Oil terminal|tank farm]],<ref name="vanguardnigeria2">{{cite news |newspaper= [[Vanguard (Nigeria)]] |title= Petrolex Group to launch Sub-Saharan Africa’s largest tank farm |url= https://www.vanguardngr.com/2017/12/petrolex-group-launch-sub-saharan-africas-largest-tank-farm/ |date= 7 December 2017 }}</ref><ref name="vanguardnigeria3">{{cite news |newspaper= [[Vanguard (Nigeria)]] |title= $330m Petrolex mega oil city to ease Apapa gridlock by 60% |url= https://www.vanguardngr.com/2017/12/330m-petrolex-mega-oil-city-ease-apapa-gridlock-60/ |date= 8 December 2017 }}</ref> a liquefied petroleum gas processing plant, a lubricant facility and [[raw material]] industries (ex. fertiliser plants). The company has also negotiated the addition of 12,000 acres to expand the Oil City.<ref name="sunnigeria1"/><ref name="leadernigeria1">{{cite news |newspaper= [[Leadership (newspaper)|Leadership (Nigeria)]] |title= Petrolex To Invest $6bn In Refinery, Power Plant, Others |url= https://leadership.ng/2017/12/11/petrolex-invest-6bn-refinery-power-plant-others/ |date= 11 January 2017 }}</ref>
==Operations overview==
===Downstream operations===
Petrolex [[Downstream (petroleum industry)|downstream]] operations include the processing of petroleum products, the supply and distribution of gas oil, kerosene; and the retail marketing of specific oil products. Petrolex has built a storage-tank farm and other “mid-stream infrastructure” for $330 million.<ref name="bloomnigeria1"/> The company is connecting its infrastructure to the Nigeria System 2B pipeline at Mosimi to support supply and distribution of petroleum products around the country. This infrastructure includes a procurement of barges, tug boats and a daughter vessel.<ref name="newtelegranigeria1"/>
