{{refimprove|date=February 2013}} [[File:Czech-03836 - Metronome (32638405050).jpg|right|thumb|The Metronome]]
The '''Metronome''' is a {{convert|75|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} functioning [[metronome]] in [[Letná Park]], overlooking the [[Vltava River]] and the city center of [[Prague]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Prague Metronome |url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/prague-metronome |work=Atlas Obscura |language=en}}</ref> It was erected in 1991, on the plinth left vacant by the demolition in 1962 of an [[Stalin Monument (Prague)|enormous monument to former Soviet leader Joseph Stalin]]. The metronome was designed by international artist [[Vratislav Novak]].<ref>[[Mariusz Czepczyński]], ''Cultural Landscapes of Post-Socialist Cities: Representation of Powers and Needs'', Ashgate, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-7546-7022-3}}, [https://books.google.com.co/books?id=ztVJLYq9WtoC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=vratislav+novak+stalin+monument&source=bl&ots=ChcM4bmNL9&sig=pHlIZ32owtb2LTc5qMWKkJCjRAo&hl=de&sa=X&ei=-0cAUbC8DZKs8QTrroDYAQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=vratislav%20novak%20stalin%20monument&f=false Google Print, p.94]</ref>
Although the metronome is functional, it is not always in operation.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Red Metronome: Prague&#8217;s Communist Past |url=https://www.popmatters.com/189644-the-red-metronome-pragues-communist-past-2495571806.html |accessdate=29 July 2018 |work=PopMatters |date=12 February 2015 |language=en}}</ref> The site is now mostly a scenic vista and a meeting place for young people.
